<font size="3" color="red">Private Repositories</font>

If you have access to a so-called private repository (or wish to create your own), there are two options for integrating it into CA

<li>Create a folder called <strong>/boot/config/plugins/community.applications/repositoryName</strong><br>

Within this folder, place any custom / private templates you might have.  (If using the dockerHub conversion section of this plugin, a folder will be automatically created here called <strong>dockerHub</strong><br>

Or alternatively,

<li>Create a GitHub repository, and then on your flash drive, create a file called <strong>/boot/config/plugins/community.applications/private.repositories.json</strong>
<br>This file has the following format:
<blockquote>
[<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;{<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;"name": "Whatever you want to call the repository",<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;"url":&nbsp;&nbsp;"the full URL to the GitHub repository"<br>
&nbsp;&nbsp;}<br>
]
</blockquote>


In either case, the templates contained in the private repository will be flagged when displayed as <font color="red">Private</font>

<strong>NOTE:</strong> Storing the private templates on the flash drive is the recommended way of creating a private repository</strong>
